# Cursor artefacts are committed, not ignored

This repo treats Cursor's generated artefacts as first-class historical record:
they document why decisions were made, what rules guide future work, and which
plans shaped each release. Don't leave them dangling as untracked files.

## Always commit

| Path | What it is |
|---|---|
| `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` | Rules that guide AI behaviour in this project |
| `.cursor/plans/*.plan.md` | Plans the agent produced for multi-step work |
| `docs/cursor_*.md` | Session transcripts exported from Cursor |

When you finish a session, before suggesting "all done", check `git status`. If
any of the above appear as untracked or modified, fold them into the relevant
work commit (or a small follow-up commit) with a clear message referencing
their origin.

## Commit message conventions

- New transcripts:  `Add session transcript: <short title>`
- New plans:       `Add plan: <plan name>`
- Rule changes:    explain *why* in the body, not just *what* (rules outlast
                   the situations they were written for)

## Don't

- Don't add these paths to `.gitignore`.
- Don't strip them from `git status` reports to the user just because they're
  "auto-generated" - they're part of the project's reasoning trail.

## When unsure

If a `docs/cursor_*.md` looks redundant with another committed transcript, ask
the user before deleting; otherwise commit it. The cost of an extra committed
markdown file is near zero; the cost of losing a session's reasoning is real.
